kage.json\n  - .gitignore\n  - README.md\n```\n\n### API Endpoints\n- **GET /todos**: Fetch all todo items.\n- **POST /todos**: Create a new todo item.\n- **GET /todos/{id}**: Retrieve a specific todo item by ID.\n- **PUT /todos/{id}**: Update a specific todo item by ID.\n- **DELETE /todos/{id}**: Delete a specific todo item by ID.\n\n### Data Flow\n1. Incoming HTTP request hits the Express server.\n2. The server routes the request to the appropriate controller function via `routes`.\n3. Controller function processes the request, using `models` to interact with MongoDB.\n4. Perform CRUD operations on the database.\n5. Results are sent back to the client as JSON responses.\n\n### Database Schema (Mongoose)\n```javascript\nconst mongoose = require('mongoose');\n\nconst todoSchema = new mongoose.Schema({\n  title: { type: String, required: true },\n  description: { type: String },\n  completed: { type: Boolean, default: false },\n  due_date: { type: Date },\n}, {\n  timestamps: true\n});\n\nmodule.exports = mongoose.model('Todo', todoSchema);\n```\n\n### Authentication (JWT)\n- Implement middleware to protect routes.\n- Use JWTs for token-based authentication on protected routes (if applicable).\n\n### Summary\nThis architecture leverages Node.js, Express, and MongoDB to create a REST API that is both scalable and maintainable. This setup provides a solid foundation for handling CRUD operations required by a todo app while allowing for future enhancements such as user authentication or additional features.\n\nARCHITECTURE COMPLETE", type='TextMessage'), inner_messages=[]), 'name': 'Architect'}
